description: The Andromeda Galaxy, M31, is a spiral galaxy approximately 2.5 million light-years (780 kiloparsecs) away in the constellation Andromeda. Being approximately 220,000 light years across, it is the largest galaxy of the Local Group, which includes the Milky Way, the Triangulum Galaxy and about 44 other smaller galaxies. Best seen in the optical DSS2 sky. Read more

The Triangulum Galaxy, M33, is a spiral galaxy approximately 3 million light-years away in the constellation Triangulum. It is the third largest member of the Local Group of galaxies, which includes the Milky Way, the Andromeda Galaxy and about 44 other smaller galaxies. Best seen in the optical DSS2 sky. Read more

The Whirlpool Galaxy, M51, is an interacting spiral galaxy with a Seyfert 2 active galactic nucleus and is approximately 23 million light-years away in the constellation Canes Venatici. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
M83, also known as the Southern Pinwheel Galaxy, is a barred spiral galaxy approximately 15 million light-years away in the constellation Hydra. Best seen in the optical DSS2 sky. Read more
M91 is a barred spiral galaxy approximately 63 million light-years away in the Coma Berenices constellation and is part of the Virgo Cluster of galaxies. Best seen in the optical DSS2 sky. Read more
M95 is a barred spiral galaxy approximately 38 million light-years away in the constellation Leo. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
M99 is an unbarred spiral galaxy approximately 50 million light-years away in the constellation Coma Berenices. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more

M100 is a spiral galaxy approximately 55 million light-years away in the constellation Coma Berenices. It has a diameter of 107,000 light years and is one of the brightest and largest galaxies in the Virgo Cluster. Best seen in the optical DSS2 sky. Read more
M101, also known as the Pinwheel Galaxy, is a spiral galaxy approximately 21 million light-years away in the constellation Ursa Major. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
